Class PriorityQueue

  • java.lang.Object
    • PriorityQueue
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Queue<Assignment>

    public class PriorityQueue
extends java.lang.Object
implements Queue<Assignment>
    This class is a LinkedList Queue implementation that uses PriorityQueue.Node that points both to the next Node and to the previous, as well as maintains itself in a sort so that the highest priority Assignment is removed every time. Implementation requires non-generic due to requiring direct acccess to attributes of Assignment.
    Author:
    Aidan Novobilski

      • add

        private void add(Assignment data,
                 PriorityQueue.Node prior)
        This add method attempts to add data at a specific index. If the specified index is greater than the number of entries, it will be added on the end anyway. Used by enqueue(Assignment) to sort the array to maintain priority.
        Parameters:
        data - the data to add
        prior - the node before the position to add to

      • compare

        private int compare(Assignment inQ,
                    Assignment toAdd)
        This method acts as a "safe" comparison, handling cases in which Assignment.compareTo(Assignment) would result in division by 0. If one has 0 days left and another does not, the one with zero days remaining is higher priority. If they both have 0 days left, their pure value is compared. Otherwise, Assignment.compareTo(Assignment) occurs normally.
        Parameters:
        inQ - the assignment in queue to be checked
        toAdd - the assignment to be added
        Returns:
        a number similar to Assignment.compareTo(Assignment)
